column51: For a new teacher, this was a difficult site to navigate. It took forever for me to figure out how to get flyers for my students to take home to parents. Many of my parents aren't interested in digital flyers.  Also, I teach special education and most of my students are not reading on grade level so sending home flyers that say kindergarten or 1st grade is a little off-putting to parents of 4th and 5th graders. maybe leave that off the flyer that goes home. Or modify it somehow.  I also teach a range of grades which is complicated when selecting how many students I have. I understand that most of your clientele is full classrooms of 25-30 students, but I end up with an excess of left over flyers. Not sure if the trees can be saved or if money can be saved by not having to send out so many. If not, then oh well.

column51: Every year, I buy some books, and I work hard to get my students to buy books so that I have enough bonus points to get them all a book as a gift at the end of the year.  This year, you have made the most affordable books not applicable for bonus point use.  This makes it impossible for a teacher to buy a class set of books to give as gifts to her students.  I do not have the money to spend $50 or more on buying my students books that they can take home at the end of the year.  So instead of using my points here to get them each a book, I will have to buy them all a pencil or something that I can afford.  This is a real sad thing you have done.  I may choose not to use Scholastic in the future if my bonus point cannot be used for the things I need for my students.

column51: I teach in a Title 1, high needs school and very often buy shoes, etc for my young scholars.  Many of my kids have no books at home so I am always happy to share from my classroom library.   I am disappointed that you no longer offer $1.00 books in your fliers each month.  I use your books as an incentive for my kids when they reach their reading or math goals.  They love being able to choose a book of their own.  We have a PTO fundraiser each week where kids can bring money to purchase popcorn, etc.  For years I would give my kids the choice of also buying a $1.00 book from your fliers.  Most of the kids would choose a book!  To reach $75.00 for my orders to be able to open the $1.00 books means I have to purchase books myself and that is not something I am able to do.

column51: I only would "refer another teacher" to your company because there is no other option!  So sad that you are "building back" --after HORRENDOUS service during and post-COVID--at the literal expense of teachers!  (higher prices, fewer "deals,"  S & H fees, locked "deals" unless one orders a certain amount, accounting issues for teachers to justify,   etc.)    I've been ordering from Scholastic for 30+ years- but your current policy to  CHARGE teachers for S & H when an order is not at $25 is complete and utter nonsense!  You have "the corner" on book clubs and book fairs in this country....I highly doubt that your "bottom line" is at risk if I am not charged $6.50 to get books sent to me!! (On behalf of my students)  What a joke!  Your company often brags using phrases such as "we support teachers" and  we offer "quality literature at low prices."  Where are the ACTIONS behind those words?  I guess there is no need to truly support & help teachers because you know we have no other option

column51: I can't believe you're not allowing teachers to use bonus points for the end-of-year gift books.  I understand that it is a great deal, but if it is an end-of-year gift, teachers are obviously purchasing for their ENTIRE class.  We have HUGE class sizes so $2/student adds up quickly.  I was also frustrated to see that I don't get the $10 bonus until my May order.  Most teachers don't place orders in May because it's too close to the end of the year, which is probably why you did that because you know we won't spend it.  It's obvious that you're trying to gauge teachers who already spend a TON of their own money on their students.  Shame on you!  Also, the overall quality of your books in terrible.  Pages are falling out constantly.

column51: I wish I could search by price or item type.  Sometimes I may search puzzles or decodable books, etc. and although it is in the title of the item, the item does not come up.  It seems like a glitch in the search.  Overall, I think the site is easy and user friendly.  I love to search for learning materials, not just books.  I wish there were more in the fliers.  The students often want the puzzles, games, etc. that I have purchased from Scholastic over the years.  I wish you also still had big books.  Thank you for the great site!

column51: Ordering and using bonus points.   This was one of the worst order sessions I have had since Scholastic allowed online orders. Just credit the points to teachers' accounts instead of making them jump through hoops to get the extra bonus points. I have not ordered as often as of late because of how time consuming it is to select books I think the students will like and how time consuming it is to use bonus points wisely. FRUSTRATING!!!!! I appreciate getting the bonus points, but I always feel I am not using them as well as I could. It takes to long to try to figure out how many one has left after placing the teacher order.

column51: I've been a Scholastic customer for many, many years now and am so disappointed with the switch that you won't get your free books until the next month.  There are some months that I'm not allowed to send home the flyer because we have a book fair at my school 2 times a year..  That book fair is also Scholastic!    The $10 teachers get a month with their order, the bonus points and the free book pack are the only reason I send home the flyers and do the order!  I teach in a very wealthy district and my kids do not need to buy any other books.     I will not recommend this anymore to new teachers-

column51: I get confused by the number of Scholastic sites there are to shop at. First I logged into the regular Scholastic site and was shopping, but then I realized I wasn't using the same website as what was on the flyer my daughter got from her teacher (scholastic.com/bookclubs). The same login works on both sites, but I wasn't able to find the same books on both sites. BUT, the books on the site from the flyer were cheaper than on the regular site. Seemed odd, but I'm not complaining...

column7: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/112.0.0.0 Safari/537.36
column51: I am super disappointed that teachers don't get their $10 to spend RIGHT NOW and we receive a $10 coupon in the book box to spend for NEXT month.   I teach at a low income school, so I do not send home book orders every month, but rather every other month.  I don't need another reason for parents to say no to their child when they can't financially afford to order books all the time.   If anything, this hurts ME, the teacher.  I waste my $10 coupon because I don't want to spend more of my own money to pay for shipping.  Please go back to your old method and don't hurt us teachers!!!

column51: I get so frustrated with the search engine function.  Today, I wanted to filter by several grade levels and several formats.  Each time I click the + sign to select options, I can only select 1 before the screen closes and then I have to scroll back up, click another choice, wait for it to close and then repeat over and over.  Can the programmers all us to check MULTIPLE options instead of automatically closing after each choice?    Also, it feels like there are LESS book choices than in the past.  Maybe it's just my perception, but when trying to add to the library I keep thinking, "I already have all those books!"

column51: I love Scholastic! I think there are great options for books and the prices are very reasonable.   Two suggestions: One suggestion I have is having a lower grade level book and an upper grade level book for the $1 books each week. There was a lot of lower level books this year and my 4th graders were past that. I would have ordered more books if there were more 4th grade level book options.   Second suggestion: the $1 books that were picked this year for the upper grades did not align with their interests. A lot of the books are classics but do not seem interesting to them so we didn't order.
